## What happened

This is a **.NET 11 breaking change**: **DSA has been removed from macOS**. In .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` and all DSA signing/verification operations throw on macOS. It still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the algorithm for existing signatures. Your options:

1. **Skip macOS for DSA verification** — guard the call at runtime:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature…
   }
   else
   {
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
           "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");
   }
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** — e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography) provides a managed DSA implementation that doesn't depend on the OS:
   ```csharp
   // Works on all platforms including macOS
   var dsaParams = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(/* … */);
   var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   signer.Init(false, dsaParams);
   signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Long-term: migrate signatures to ECDSA/RSA** — re-sign artifacts with a modern algorithm so DSA is no longer needed.

For a verification-only library, **option 2** (BouncyCastle) is usually the best path — it keeps all three platforms working without re-signing existing data.
